    <node id=" with three of the best pair of eyes on the borders, in his rear.&quot;&#10;&#10;The spirits of the scout, and the astonishing success of the chase, in&#10;which a circuitous distance of more than forty miles had been passed,&#10;did not fail to impart a portion of hope to the whole party. Their&#10;advance was rapid; and made with as much confidence as a traveller would&#10;proceed along a wide highway. If a rock, or a rivulet, or a bit of earth&#10;harder than common, severed the links of the clue they followed, the&#10;true eye of the scout recovered them at a distance, and seldom rendered&#10;the delay of a single moment necessary. Their progress was much&#10;facilitated by the certainty that Magua had found it necessary to&#10;journey through the valleys; a circumstance which rendered the general&#10;direction of the route sure. Nor had the Huron entirely neglected the&#10;arts uniformly practised by the natives when retiring in front of any&#10;enemy. False trails, and sudden turnings, were frequent, wherever a&#10;brook, or the formation of the ground, rendered them feasible; but his&#10;pursuers were rarely deceived, and never failed to detect their error,&#10;before they had" />
    <node id="Based on the narrative, we can infer several things about the progress of the hunt. First, Uncas has identified a fresh trail left by an animal or person, which the scout confirms as a canoe paddled by &quot;fierce and crafty Mingos&quot; (Huron warriors). The scout seems knowledgeable and experienced in tracking, able to interpret signs that others might miss, such as the impression of a foot on a bunch of moss. He also demonstrates an awareness of the dangers of being pursued, recognizing that the Hurons will likely follow their trail once it gets dark.&#10;&#10;The party follows the trail along a rill until they reach a dry rock, where they pause to make sure the Hurons haven't left the water. Uncas then discovers a fresh footprint in the neighboring thicket, which leads them to an earthen fort. The scout advises his companions to step on stones and fragments of wood as they clamber through the ruins surrounding the fort, suggesting that he is aware of the importance of leaving no trace for their pursuers.&#10;&#10;Once they reach the other side of the fort, the scout declares that the trail is now invisible to all but those with a keen sense of smell. He dashes forward confidently, and soon after, Uncas locates the tracks of the horses that the party had been following before. The scout interprets this as a sign that they have entered enemy territory, and that the horses' riders may have abandoned them to move more quickly on foot. Overall, the scout's observations suggest that he is confident in his ability to track the Hurons and navigate the wilderness, while also recognizing the dangers that pursuers can pose." />
