    <node id=" The Native Americans are signaling a stop because they have spotted a thin streak of mist rising above an islet, with an edging of blacker smoke hanging along its lower side. This indicates the presence of a fire on the islet, which suggests the vicinity of their enemies, the Hurons or French. However, the scout cannot see this danger at first because he is focusing on detecting any signs of disturbance on the water's surface, and the calm lake appears free of such signs. It is only when Chingachgook points out the unnatural mist and the edging of blacker smoke that the scout recognizes the fire on the islet as a sign of danger." />
    <node id=" The Mohicans, Chingachgook and Uncas, show no perceptible emotion when their enemies fire volleys at them during the canoe chase. Their rigid features express neither hope nor alarm. Hawkeye, the scout, explains that this is because the enemies, who are Native American as well (Mingos or Hurons), struggle to calculate an accurate range for their bullets in a moving canoe. The canoe's motion makes it difficult for them to aim accurately, and they often need to reload after each shot, slowing down their rate of fire. Hawkeye also notes that these enemies seem to value the sound of their guns more than their accuracy. In contrast, Hawkeye deliberately waits for a clearer shot, only firing when he is satisfied with the range and his ability to hit the target." />
    <node id="op of the Mohicans, and then lent his&#10;strength and skill again to the important task.&#10;&#10;The clamorous sounds of &quot;Le Gros Serpent!&quot; &quot;La Longue Carabine!&quot; &quot;Le&#10;Cerf Agile!&quot; burst at once from the canoes behind, and seemed to give&#10;new zeal to the pursuers. The scout seized &quot;Killdeer&quot; in his left hand,&#10;and elevating it above his head, he shook it in triumph at his enemies.&#10;The savages answered the insult with a yell, and immediately another&#10;volley succeeded. The bullets pattered along the lake, and one even&#10;pierced the bark of their little vessel. No perceptible emotion could be&#10;discovered in the Mohicans during this critical moment, their rigid&#10;features expressing neither hope nor alarm; but the scout again turned&#10;his head, and laughing in his own silent manner, he said to Heyward,--&#10;&#10;&quot;The knaves love to hear the sounds of their pieces; but the eye is not&#10;to be found among the Mingos that can calculate a true range in a&#10;dancing canoe! You see the dumb devils have taken off a man to charge,&#10;and by the smallest measurement that" />
    <node id="The foresters, consisting of Heyward, Chingachgook, Uncas, and the scout, are navigating through a lake at dawn, being cautious as they suspect that Montcalm might have left some Indians in ambush along this passage. They are looking for signs of danger and carefully making their way through the intricate channels.&#10;&#10;Uncas found a clue that allowed them to continue their pursuit of the Hurons by discovering the two fillies, with their saddles broken and housings soiled, which suggests that they had been running free for several days. This discovery indicates that the party has entered enemy territory and their journey must come to an end." />
    <node id=" At the break of dawn, Hawkeye and his companions engage in several actions and follow specific instructions to ensure their safety. First, they have a canoe but lift it from the water and carry it on their shoulders into the woods, making sure to leave a broad and obvious trail. They then reach a water-course and continue through the woods with Uncas leading them towards the hills behind Ticonderoga, where Montcalm's army is known to be. After hours of cautious travel, they land the canoe at a bay near the northern terminus of the lake. Hawkeye and Heyward then ascend a bluff, where Hawkeye points out a small black object several miles away, asking Heyward to identify it.&#10;&#10;Throughout this process, Hawkeye advises Heyward not to fire his rifle under any circumstances while creeping up on their target and only do so if he sees Heyward in danger. Hawkeye also changes his mind about using his weapon when he realizes the 'savage' is unaware of their presence. This cautious behavior suggests that they are aware of potential dangers and are taking measures to avoid detection while maintaining the ability to defend themselves if necessary." />
    <node id="Ḥawkeye and his companions lift their canoe from the water, carry it into the woods, and create a broad trail as a strategic move to make it appear as if they want to be noticed. They hope that by doing so, any potential enemies will believe that they are not trying to hide and thus reduce the risk of being attacked. This action also serves as a decoy to divert attention from their actual intention, which is to approach the source of the smoke cautiously and investigate any possible danger. By creating an obvious trail, they can move through the woods more covertly while maintaining the ability to defend themselves if necessary." />
    <node id=" In the narrative, Major Duncan Heyward, Colonel Munro, and the Sagamore have decided not to engage in battle with their enemies, the Hurons, who are approaching distance. Instead, they choose to continue their journey across the lake, increasing their distance from the enemy. This decision is made after the Sagamore demonstrates that his injury, which was caused by a previous encounter with the Hurons, is minor. Heyward, in particular, emphasizes the importance of this decision by reminding the group of their main objective and purpose for traveling." />
