    <node id="Ḥawkeye advises Heyward not to fire his rifle under any circumstances while creeping up on the knave, and only to do so if he sees Heyward in danger. This instruction is conveyed through Hawkeye's response to Heyward's question about firing if he sees him in danger, where Hawkeye says &quot;Fire a whole platoon, major,&quot; implying that Heyward should use his judgment and fire only if necessary to protect himself or others from danger." />
    <node id=" The narrative does not provide a direct explanation from Heyward regarding why the Marquis of Montcalm could not prevent the massacre of the British prisoners by the Hurons. However, Heyward does mention that there is a difference between Montcalm ordering a regiment of soldiers to physically stand between the Hurons and the prisoners, and trying to persuade an angry savage to forget their desire for revenge with words. This suggests that Heyward believes Montcalm's influence over the Hurons may have limits, particularly when it comes to situations where the Hurons are driven by strong emotions such as anger or a desire for revenge. Additionally, Heyward's comment that Montcalm will have to settle the matter with his God implies that he sees the massacre as a moral failure on Montcalm's part, possibly due to an inability or unwillingness to exercise enough control over his Huron allies." />
    <node id="The discovery of the moccasin print in the moist alluvion by Uncas is significant because it provides evidence that someone had passed through the area recently. However, Hawkeye notes that the footprint does not belong to an Indian, as it has a different shape and weight distribution than that of an Indian's footprint. The weight is too much on the heel, and the toes are squared, as though one of the French dancers had been in, pigeon-winging his tribe! This suggests that the person who made the footprint is likely a non-native person wearing moccasins.&#10;&#10;Hawkeye's confusion about whether the footprint belongs to an Indian or not stems from his expertise in tracking and identifying different people's footprints. He is able to determine the size, shape, and weight distribution of a person's footprint and use that information to identify their tribe or origin. In this case, the footprint does not match any known Native American footprints, which is why Hawkeye finds it puzzling." />
    <node id=" Not a leaf was left unturned. The sticks were removed, and&#10;the stones lifted; for Indian cunning was known frequently to adopt&#10;these objects as covers, laboring with the utmost patience and industry,&#10;to conceal each footstep as they proceeded. Still no discovery was made.&#10;At length Uncas, whose activity had enabled him to achieve his portion&#10;of the task the soonest, raked the earth across the turbid little rill&#10;which ran from the spring, and diverted its course into another channel.&#10;So soon as its narrow bed below the dam was dry, he stooped over it with&#10;keen and curious eyes. A cry of exultation immediately announced the&#10;success of the young warrior. The whole party crowded to the spot where&#10;Uncas pointed out the impression of a moccasin in the moist alluvion.&#10;&#10;&quot;The lad will be an honor to his people,&quot; said Hawkeye, regarding the&#10;trail with as much admiration as a naturalist would expend on the tusk&#10;of a mammoth or the rib of a mastodon; &quot;ay, and a thorn in the sides of&#10;the Hurons. Yet that is not the footstep of an Indian! the weight is too&#10;much" />
