    <edge source=" the work with an&#10;eagerness that supplied the place of skill, while Hawkeye was engaged in&#10;inspecting the priming of his rifle. The latter then took a swift aim,&#10;and fired. The Huron in the bows of the leading canoe had risen with a&#10;similar object, and he now fell backward, suffering his gun to escape&#10;from his hands into the water. In an instant, however, he recovered his&#10;feet, though his gestures were wild and bewildered. At the same moment&#10;his companions suspended their efforts, and the chasing canoes clustered&#10;together, and became stationary. Chingachgook and Uncas profited by the&#10;interval to regain their wind, though Duncan continued to work with the&#10;most persevering industry. The father and son now cast calm but&#10;inquiring glances at each other, to learn if either had sustained any&#10;injury by the fire; for both well knew that no cry or exclamation would,&#10;in such a moment of necessity, have been permitted to betray the&#10;accident. A few large drops of blood were trickling down the shoulder of&#10;the Sagamore, who, when he perceived that the eyes of Uncas dwelt too&#10;long on the sight" target=" In this narrative, there is a tense moment in a canoe chase during a battle where Uncas and Chingachgook, both Native American warriors, display different reactions to the danger they face. The context of the scene involves their enemies, who are also Native Americans, shooting at them with guns from other canoes. However, due to the motion of the canoe and the inaccuracy of their enemies' aim, they struggle to hit their targets. Hawkeye, a skilled scout, deliberately waits for a clear shot before firing his rifle, while their enemies fire many shots that miss.&#10;&#10;Uncas, a young warrior, shows amazement at the willingness of Duncan and Munro to expose themselves to such danger. Meanwhile, Chingachgook, a more experienced warrior, remains focused on steering the canoe with a riveted look, unfazed by the gunfire around him. The enemies' shots are described as being less about accuracy and more about making noise.&#10;&#10;Later, when they see signs of danger, such as a thin streak of mist rising above an islet with blacker smoke hanging along its lower side, it's Chingachgook who first notices the unnatural mist and points it out to the scout. This shows how skilled and vigilant they are in detecting danger.&#10;&#10;In summary, during a tense moment in a canoe chase amidst a battle, Uncas displays amazement while Chingachgook remains calm and focused, demonstrating their differing reactions to danger based on their experience and skill level. Chingachgook's quick observation of danger highlights the importance of situational awareness in survival situations.">
