    <edge source=" Hawkeye advises Heyward to not fire his rifle under any circumstances while he creeps up on the knave through the bush, and to only do so if he sees Heyward in danger." target=" The Native Americans are signaling a stop because they have spotted a thin streak of mist rising above an islet, with an edging of blacker smoke hanging along its lower side. This indicates the presence of a fire on the islet, which suggests the vicinity of their enemies, the Hurons or French. However, the scout cannot see this danger at first because he is focusing on detecting any signs of disturbance on the water's surface, and the calm lake appears free of such signs. It is only when Chingachgook points out the unnatural mist and the edging of blacker smoke that the scout recognizes the fire on the islet as a sign of danger.">
