    <edge source=" Hawkeye advises Heyward to not fire his rifle under any circumstances while he creeps up on the knave through the bush, and to only do so if he sees Heyward in danger." target=" At the break of dawn, Hawkeye and his companions engage in several actions and follow specific instructions to ensure their safety. First, they have a canoe but lift it from the water and carry it on their shoulders into the woods, making sure to leave a broad and obvious trail. They then reach a water-course and continue through the woods with Uncas leading them towards the hills behind Ticonderoga, where Montcalm's army is known to be. After hours of cautious travel, they land the canoe at a bay near the northern terminus of the lake. Hawkeye and Heyward then ascend a bluff, where Hawkeye points out a small black object several miles away, asking Heyward to identify it.&#10;&#10;Throughout this process, Hawkeye advises Heyward not to fire his rifle under any circumstances while creeping up on their target and only do so if he sees Heyward in danger. Hawkeye also changes his mind about using his weapon when he realizes the 'savage' is unaware of their presence. This cautious behavior suggests that they are aware of potential dangers and are taking measures to avoid detection while maintaining the ability to defend themselves if necessary.">
