    <edge source="Based on the narrative, we can infer several things about the progress of the hunt. First, Uncas has identified a fresh trail left by an animal or person, which the scout confirms as a canoe paddled by &quot;fierce and crafty Mingos&quot; (Huron warriors). The scout seems knowledgeable and experienced in tracking, able to interpret signs that others might miss, such as the impression of a foot on a bunch of moss. He also demonstrates an awareness of the dangers of being pursued, recognizing that the Hurons will likely follow their trail once it gets dark.&#10;&#10;The party follows the trail along a rill until they reach a dry rock, where they pause to make sure the Hurons haven't left the water. Uncas then discovers a fresh footprint in the neighboring thicket, which leads them to an earthen fort. The scout advises his companions to step on stones and fragments of wood as they clamber through the ruins surrounding the fort, suggesting that he is aware of the importance of leaving no trace for their pursuers.&#10;&#10;Once they reach the other side of the fort, the scout declares that the trail is now invisible to all but those with a keen sense of smell. He dashes forward confidently, and soon after, Uncas locates the tracks of the horses that the party had been following before. The scout interprets this as a sign that they have entered enemy territory, and that the horses' riders may have abandoned them to move more quickly on foot. Overall, the scout's observations suggest that he is confident in his ability to track the Hurons and navigate the wilderness, while also recognizing the dangers that pursuers can pose." target=" caught the&#10;look, and motioning with his hand, he bade him speak. The moment this&#10;permission was accorded, the countenance of Uncas changed from its grave&#10;composure to a gleam of intelligence and joy. Bounding forward like a&#10;deer, he sprang up the side of a little acclivity, a few rods in&#10;advance, and stoo