    <edge source=" At the break of dawn, Hawkeye and his companions engage in several actions and follow specific instructions to ensure their safety. First, they have a canoe but lift it from the water and carry it on their shoulders into the woods, making sure to leave a broad and obvious trail. They then reach a water-course and continue through the woods with Uncas leading them towards the hills behind Ticonderoga, where Montcalm's army is known to be. After hours of cautious travel, they land the canoe at a bay near the northern terminus of the lake. Hawkeye and Heyward then ascend a bluff, where Hawkeye points out a small black object several miles away, asking Heyward to identify it.&#10;&#10;Throughout this process, Hawkeye advises Heyward not to fire his rifle under any circumstances while creeping up on their target and only do so if he sees Heyward in danger. Hawkeye also changes his mind about using his weapon when he realizes the 'savage' is unaware of their presence. This cautious behavior suggests that they are aware of potential dangers and are taking measures to avoid detection while maintaining the ability to defend themselves if necessary." target="Ḥawkeye and his companions lift their canoe from the water, carry it into the woods, and create a broad trail as a strategic move to make it appear as if they want to be noticed. They hope that by doing so, any potential enemies will believe that they are not trying to hide and thus reduce the risk of being attacked. This action also serves as a decoy to divert attention from their actual intention, which is to approach the source of the smoke cautiously and investigate any possible danger. By creating an obvious trail, they can move through the woods more covertly while maintaining the ability to defend themselves if necessary.">
