    <edge source="The discovery of the moccasin print in the moist alluvion by Uncas is significant because it provides evidence that someone had passed through the area recently. However, Hawkeye notes that the footprint does not belong to an Indian, as it has a different shape and weight distribution than that of an Indian's footprint. The weight is too much on the heel, and the toes are squared, as though one of the French dancers had been in, pigeon-winging his tribe! This suggests that the person who made the footprint is likely a non-native person wearing moccasins.&#10;&#10;Hawkeye's confusion about whether the footprint belongs to an Indian or not stems from his expertise in tracking and identifying different people's footprints. He is able to determine the size, shape, and weight distribution of a person's footprint and use that information to identify their tribe or origin. In this case, the footprint does not match any known Native American footprints, which is why Hawkeye finds it puzzling." target=" Not a leaf was left unturned. The sticks were removed, and&#10;the stones lifted; for Indian cunning was known frequently to adopt&#10;these objects as covers, laboring with the utmost patience and industry,&#10;to conceal each footstep as they proceeded. Still no discovery was made.&#10;At length Uncas, whose activity had enabled him to achieve his portion&#10;of the task the soonest, raked the earth across the turbid little rill&#10;which ran from the spring, and diverted its course into another channel.&#10;So soon as its narrow bed below the dam was dry, he stooped over it with&#10;keen and curious eyes. A cry of exultation immediately announced the&#10;success of the young warrior. The whole party crowded to the spot where&#10;Uncas pointed out the impression of a moccasin in the moist alluvion.&#10;&#10;&quot;The lad will be an honor to his people,&quot; said Hawkeye, regarding the&#10;trail with as much admiration as a naturalist would expend on the tusk&#10;of a mammoth or the rib of a mastodon; &quot;ay, and a thorn in the sides of&#10;the Hurons. Yet that is not the footstep of an Indian! the weight is too&#10;much">
